This patch addresses a noisy `ld.lld` warning around the timer-OF table
sentinel used by `drivers/clocksource/timer-probe.c`.

In Linux `6.18`, `timer-probe.c` is built whenever `CONFIG_TIMER_PROBE=y`.
That can happen through either `CONFIG_TIMER_OF` or `CONFIG_TIMER_ACPI`, but
the timer-OF linker table is only emitted when `CONFIG_TIMER_OF=y`.

On ACPI-only builds with `CONFIG_TIMER_ACPI=y` and `CONFIG_TIMER_OF=n`, the
trailing timer-OF sentinel was still emitted into `__timer_of_table_end` even
though the linker script intentionally emitted no timer-OF table. `ld.lld`
then reports the sentinel input section as an orphan:

  vmlinux.o:(__timer_of_table_end) is being placed in '__timer_of_table_end'

Do not create a synthetic timer-OF linker table just to consume the sentinel:
that changes the ACPI-only link layout for no runtime benefit. Instead, emit
the sentinel only when the timer-OF table itself is enabled. This preserves the
existing linker-script behaviour for `CONFIG_TIMER_OF=y` and removes the orphan
section for ACPI-only builds.

diff --git a/drivers/clocksource/timer-probe.c b/drivers/clocksource/timer-probe.c
--- a/drivers/clocksource/timer-probe.c
+++ b/drivers/clocksource/timer-probe.c
@@ -10,8 +10,10 @@
 
 extern struct of_device_id __timer_of_table[];
 
+#ifdef CONFIG_TIMER_OF
 static const struct of_device_id __timer_of_table_sentinel
 	__used __section("__timer_of_table_end");
+#endif
 
 void __init timer_probe(void)
 {
